BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ighhNLEHiRaO2WfWPfpg1
SUMMARY:Programmable control of small non-coding RNA expression in mammalia
	n cells with synthetic RNA polymerase III transactivators.
DTSTAMP:20260629T025255Z
DTSTART:20260710T200000Z
DESCRIPTION:&#160\;  Speaker: Matthew Demelo  Doctoral Candidate  Thesis De
	fense  Department: BioSciences-Biochemistry and Cell Biology  Location: Ke
	ck Hall 102  Reliable control of gene expression via synthetic genetic cir
	cuits is essential to develop next-generation therapies\, to facilitate ef
	ficient bioindustrial processes\, and to enable advanced methods in basic 
	cell biology. Synthetic control of small non-coding RNAs (sncRNAs) is of i
	mmense interest due to their important roles in development and disease in
	 mammals\, as well as their central role in technologies such as CRISPR/Ca
	s gene editing and RNA interference. RNA polymerase III (Pol III) is the c
	anonical polymerase for sncRNA expression\, but few tools for regulated Po
	l III expression exist\, requiring expression from RNA polymerase II (Pol 
	II) promoters. While there has been extensive development of synthetic reg
	ulatory methods for expressing protein-coding RNAs and large non-coding RN
	As via Pol II\, these methods are often ineffective for robust expression 
	of functional sncRNAs and often require post-transcriptional processing fo
	r sncRNAs to achieve functionality\, impairing the feasibility of translat
	ing sncRNA technologies into medical and industrial applications. Here\, I
	 develop a toolkit capable of highly programmable and multiplexable expres
	sion of synthetic sncRNAs using Synthetic Pol III Transcription Factors (S
	yn3TFs)\, facilitating far more effective and robust expression of sncRNAs
	 in mammals than previous methods. Additionally\, I outline concise design
	 rules for the construction of minimal Pol III promoters and complementary
	 Syn3TFs\, facilitating seamless construction of orthogonal Pol III circui
	ts with customizable outputs. Finally\, I demonstrate the utility of Syn3T
	Fs in performing complex genetic logic and acting as efficient sensors for
	 continuous molecular recording of cellular events. This platform represen
	ts a crucial first step to expanding the arsenal of circuit construction s
	trategies for sncRNA expression and provides a strong foundation for conti
	nued development of Pol III-specific synthetic regulators.  &#160\;  (Depa
	rtment : BioSciences-Biochemistry and Cell Biology)\n\nhttps://events.rice
	.edu/live/events/432246-programmable-control-of-small-non-coding-rna\n\nFr
	om Rice University - Open to the Public
URL:https://events.rice.edu/live/events/432246-programmable-control-of-smal
	l-non-coding-rna
GEO:29.7174;-95.4018
LOCATION:Keck Hall
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:rice-public-events
CATEGORIES:Rice University - Open to the Public
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT1H
END:VEVENT
